<paragraph blockId="0.[839,1467,1322,1640]" pageId="0" pageNumber="87">
I have seen three Australian species of this genus belonging in the subgenera 
<emphasis box="[1027,1094,1352,1375]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="87">Apops</emphasis>
McAlpine and 
<emphasis box="[1268,1318,1352,1375]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="87">Dete</emphasis>
McAlpine as distinguished by 
<bibRefCitation author="McAlpine" box="[1020,1209,1381,1405]" firstAuthor="McAlpine" pageId="0" pageNumber="87" pagination="181 - 188" refId="ref2869" refString="McAlpine, D. K. 1994. A new Australian species of pseudopomyzid fly (Diptera: Nerioidea) and the subgenera of Pseudopomyza. Proceedings of the Linnean Society of New South Wales 114: 181 - 188." type="journal article" year="1994">McAlpine (1994)</bibRefCitation>
. Of these, one species is known only from a single female specimen from 
<collectingRegion country="Australia" name="Western Australia" pageId="0" pageNumber="87">Western Australia</collectingRegion>
which is here considered as inadequate material for taxonomic description. It is provisionally identified as 
<taxonomicName authority="" box="[839,1090,1498,1522]" class="Insecta" family="Cypselosomatidae" genus="Pseudopomyza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="87" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Apops">
<emphasis box="[839,1090,1498,1522]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="87">Pseudopomyza (Apops)</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. C, deposited at ANIC.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="87" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="0.[839,1467,1322,1640]" pageId="0" pageNumber="87">The three known Australian species have the following characters in common: two pairs of fronto-orbital bristles present; four pairs of dorsocentral bristles present; anterior intra-alar bristle absent.</paragraph>
